      <title>Venezuela reports first case of polio since 1989</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANA young child is reportedly afflicted with polio in Venezuela  the first reported case of the crippling disease since it's eradication in the country in 1989.The Telegraph reports that according to the Pan-American Health Organization, the child lived in an impoverished indigenous community in the Delta Amacuro state.According to the CDC, poliomyelitis, or polio, is caused by the poliovirus, which enters through the mouth via contact with contaminated feces, or through droplets from a cough or sneeze.The virus multiplies in small intestine, before being carried through the bloodstream to the central nervous system, where it destroys motor neuron cells.The majority of infected don't get sick, while one in four develop non-paralytic polio with flu-like symptoms. Paralytic polio, though rare, can lead to muscle pain, paralysis, and even death.In some cases, those who contracted and fully recovered from the disease as kids can develop symptoms years later as adults.Young children, especially those who are malnourished an unvaccinated, are especially susceptible to polio. The disease has no cure, but is preventable through immunization.Venezuela has been plagued with economic and political crises in recent years. Local health authorities who were supposed to report cases of polio within 24 hours, took more than a month to do so.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Depiction of how poliovirus is contracted2. Depiction of poliovirus multiplying and attacking nervous system3. Depiction of types of polio4. Depiction of polio immunizationVOICEOVER (in English): "Poliomyelitis is caused by the poliovirus, which enters through the mouth via contact with contaminated feces, or through droplets from a cough or sneeze.""The virus multiplies in small intestine, before being carried through the bloodstream to the central nervous system, where it destroys motor neuron cells.""According to the CDC, the majority of infected don't get sick, while 1 in 4 develop non-paralytic polio with flu-like symptoms. Paralytic polio, though rare, can lead to muscle pain, paralysis, and even death.""Young children, especially those who are malnourished and unvaccinated, are especially susceptible to polio. The disease has no cure, but is preventable through immunization."SOURCES: Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, Mayo Clinic, Smithsonian National Museum of American Historyhttps://www.cdc.gov/polio/about/https://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/polio/symptoms-causes/syc-20376512https://amhistory.si.edu/polio/virusvaccine/how.htm***]]></description>
