      <title>Orlando airport implements facial recognition for international travelers</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANOrlando's main airport hub is implementing facial recognition technology for international travelers. The Orlando Sentinel reports that Florida's Orlando International Airport is set to be the first U.S. airport to use facial scanners to process passengers on all inbound and outbound international flights.The scans will be checked against passenger passport photos and travel information on a Department of Homeland Security database, to verify a travelers identity.Biometric screening is expected to speed up passenger processing, but concerns have been voiced over privacy and potential information theft.In response, the U.S. Customs and Border Protection says scans in the database are deleted after 14 days, but could be removed almost immediately in the future. Photos of foreign nationals, however, are also kept in the Automated Biometric Identification System for up to 75 years.The system currently claims to have a 99% accuracy rate, though officials can manually screen passports and fingerprints if a photo doesn't match or a U.S. citizen decides to opt out.Once fully implemented, facial scanners will be stationed inside the airport's 30 international departure gates and two CBP checkpoints. The technology is also being used in other U.S. airports, though to a lesser degree.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Depiction of facial scanners being used at Orlando airport2. Depiction of face scans checked against stored biometric information3. Depiction of scans being deleted from the database after 14 days4. Depiction of traditional screening if photo doesn't match, or citizen opts outVOICEOVER (in English): "Orlando International Airport is set to be the first airport in the U.S. to use facial recognition to process passengers on all inbound and outbound international flights.""The scans will be checked against passenger passport photos and travel information on a Department of Homeland Security database, to verify a traveler's identity.""U.S. Customs and Border Protection claims scans in the database are deleted after 14 days, but could be removed almost immediately in the future.""The system currently has a 99% accuracy rate, though officials can manually screen passports and fingerprints if a photo doesn't match or a U.S. citizen decides to opt out."SOURCES: WKMG, Orlando Sentinel, News13https://www.clickorlando.com/news/what-to-know-about-the-new-facial-recognition-technology-at-orlando-international-airporthttp://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/transportation/os-orlando-airport-facial-recognition-20180621-story.htmlhttp://www.mynews13.com/fl/orlando/news/2018/06/21/oia-to-use-facial-recognition-tech-at-airport***]]></description>
