      <title>JAXA space probe arrives near asteroid</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANA Japanese space probe has reached its destination after travelling through space for three years.The Hayabusa 2 spacecraft blasted off in December 2014, Reuters reports. This week it arrived at its destination, Asteroid Ryugu, some 3 billion kilometers from Earth.Reuters reports Hayabusa 2 will orbit the asteroid for a few months in order to map its surface before it attempts a landing. The probe will use explosives and a cannon to craft a hole the surface, then collect from samples from the area.After the Hayabusa 2 has finished its work on the asteroid, the probe will begin a year-and-a-half journey back to Earth. It's expected to return in 2020.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Depiction of Hayabusa-2 flight path2. Depiction of Hayabusa-2 near asteroid and mapping it3. Depiction of Hayabusa-2 collecting samples4. Depiction of Hayabusa-2 coming back to Earth VOICEOVER (in English): "Reuters reports the Hayabusa 2 spacecraft blasted off in December 2014.""This week it arrived at its destination, Asteroid Ryugu, some 3 billion kilometers from Earth.""Reuters reports Hayabusa 2 will orbit the asteroid for a few months in order to map its surface before it attempts a landing.""The probe will use explosives and a cannon to craft a hole the surface, then collect from samples from the area.""After the Hayabusa 2 has finished its work on the asteroid, the probe will begin a year-and-a-half journey back to Earth. It's expected to return in 2020."SOURCES: JAXA, Reuters, Space http://global.jaxa.jphttps://www.reuters.com/article/us-space-japan-probe/japan-probe-arrives-at-asteroid-after-nearly-four-year-space-odyssey-idUSKBN1JN0F1https://www.space.com/41014-japanese-hayabusa2-probe-arri